<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,440,1008]" pageId="3" pageNumber="154">
<typeStatus box="[151,207,477,503]" pageId="3" pageNumber="154">Type</typeStatus>
data: 
<bibRefCitation author="Smith, F." box="[274,422,476,503]" pageId="3" pageNumber="154" pagination="199 - 465" refId="ref19938" refString="Smith, F. (1854) Catalogue of Hymenopterous Insects in the Collection of the British Museum. Part 2. British Museum, London, 267 pp. [pp. 199 - 465]" type="book chapter" year="1854">Smith (1854)</bibRefCitation>
did not specify the number of specimens he used to describe this species but he included at least one male and one female collected in Santarém, northern 
<collectingCountry box="[933,1005,513,539]" name="Brazil" pageId="3" pageNumber="154">Brazil</collectingCountry>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Baker, D. B." box="[1016,1164,513,539]" pageId="3" pageNumber="154" refId="ref17669" refString="Baker, D. B. (1993) The type material of the nominal species of exotic bees described by Frederick Smith (Hymenoptera: Apoi- dea). Ph. D. Thesis, University of Oxford, Oxford, 312 pp." type="book" year="1993">Baker (1993)</bibRefCitation>
mentioned that the 
<typeStatus box="[1388,1436,513,539]" pageId="3" pageNumber="154">type</typeStatus>
series was composed of two females and one male and that the 
<collectionCode box="[941,1047,549,575]" country="United Kingdom" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34665" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34665" name="Natural History Museum, London" pageId="3" pageNumber="154" type="Museum">NHMUK</collectionCode>
accession book indicates that they were part of material collected by the British naturalist and explorer Henry Walter Bates (
<date box="[1250,1379,584,611]" pageId="3" pageNumber="154" value="1825" valueMax="1892">1825–1892</date>
) “on the banks of the Rio Tapajos”. In 1848, Bates and Wallace made a trip to the Amazon to collect specimens. At the end of 
<date box="[378,495,657,683]" pageId="3" pageNumber="154" value="1848-05">May 1848</date>
, both arrived in 
<collectingRegion box="[676,786,657,683]" country="Brazil" name="Para" pageId="3" pageNumber="154">Pará state</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[797,868,657,683]" name="Brazil" pageId="3" pageNumber="154">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, near the mouth of the Amazon River. Bates stayed 11 years, exploring the Amazon Valley, where he collected several thousand species, mostly insects (
<bibRefCitation author="Bates, H. W." pageId="3" pageNumber="154" refId="ref17751" refString="Bates, H. W. (1863) The Naturalist on the River Amazons: A record of adventures, habits of animals, sketches of Brazilian and Indian life and aspects of nature under the Equator during eleven years of travel. Vol. 1. John Murray, London, 351 pp. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 21335" type="book" year="1863">Bates, 1863</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Van Wyhe, J." box="[299,493,729,755]" pageId="3" pageNumber="154" pagination="627 - 659" refId="ref20822" refString="Van Wyhe, J. (2014) A delicate adjustment: Wallace and Bates on the Amazon and &quot; the problem of the Origin of Species &quot;. Journal of the History of Biology, 47, 627 - 659. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / s 10739 - 014 - 9378 - z" type="journal article" year="2014">Van Wyhe, 2014</bibRefCitation>
). Among the numerous specimens collected would have been those used by 
<bibRefCitation author="Smith, F." pageId="3" pageNumber="154" pagination="199 - 465" refId="ref19938" refString="Smith, F. (1854) Catalogue of Hymenopterous Insects in the Collection of the British Museum. Part 2. British Museum, London, 267 pp. [pp. 199 - 465]" type="book chapter" year="1854">Smith (1854)</bibRefCitation>
to describe 
<taxonomicName box="[437,571,765,791]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Centris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="154" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="plumipes">
<emphasis box="[437,456,765,791]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="154">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[470,571,765,791]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="154">plumipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,440,1008]" pageId="3" pageNumber="154">
A single female of the type series was found at 
<collectionCode box="[675,781,801,827]" country="United Kingdom" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34665" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34665" name="Natural History Museum, London" pageId="3" pageNumber="154" type="Museum">NHMUK</collectionCode>
and is here designated the 
<typeStatus box="[1081,1187,801,827]" pageId="3" pageNumber="154">lectotype</typeStatus>
. The specimen has the following data label: Type H. 
<collectionCode box="[556,575,837,863]" name="Tavera, Department of Geology and Geophysics" pageId="3" pageNumber="154">T</collectionCode>
. [red-rimmed circular label, printed]\ Braz Tapajoz [circular label, handwritten]\ B.M. 
<collectionCode box="[350,420,873,899]" pageId="3" pageNumber="154">TYPE</collectionCode>
<collectionCode box="[427,496,873,899]" pageId="3" pageNumber="154">HYM</collectionCode>
. [printed] 17B.922 [handwritten]\ 
<taxonomicName authority="Sm." authorityName="Sm." box="[883,1036,873,899]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Centris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="154" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="plumipes">
<emphasis box="[883,984,873,899]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="154">plumipes</emphasis>
Sm.
</taxonomicName>
Type [handwritten]\ 
<taxonomicName authority=", Smith." authorityName="Smith." class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Centris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="154" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="plumipes">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="154">Centris plumipes</emphasis>
, Smith.
</taxonomicName>
/type. [handwritten]. Additional specimens belonging of the type series were not located and their current status is unknown, but according to 
<bibRefCitation author="Baker, D. B." box="[717,865,945,971]" pageId="3" pageNumber="154" refId="ref17669" refString="Baker, D. B. (1993) The type material of the nominal species of exotic bees described by Frederick Smith (Hymenoptera: Apoi- dea). Ph. D. Thesis, University of Oxford, Oxford, 312 pp." type="book" year="1993">Baker (1993)</bibRefCitation>
they are also housed at 
<collectionCode box="[1134,1244,945,971]" country="United Kingdom" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34665" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34665" name="Natural History Museum, London" pageId="3" pageNumber="154" type="Museum">NHMUK</collectionCode>
.
</paragraph>
